The left side is the sum of reciprocals of prime powers below `x`, while the right side is the product of terms of the form `p/(p-1)` for the first `π(x)` primes.

We can use the fact that for any prime `p`, `1 + 1/p + 1/p² + ... = 1/(1 - 1/p) = p/(p-1)`. So, the sum `∑_{k=0}^{∞} (1/p)^k` equals `p/(p-1)`.

Therefore, the sum `∑' (k : ℕ), (↑p ^ k)⁻¹` for a prime `p` is exactly `↑(p / (p - 1))`.

